We iterate through the numbers from 0 to n and convert them to binary strings. Then, we iterate through each binary string character and check if consecutive ones exist. If consecutive ones are found, we break the inner loop and skip the rest of the numbers. If no consecutive ones are found, we increment the count. Finally, we return the count. This solution has a high efficiency since it iterates through a limited range of numbers and checks each binary string character. The time complexity is O(n) because we iterate through n numbers, and the space complexity is O(1) as we only use a constant amount of space for the count variable. The energy implications are low as the solution only requires a small amount of energy consumption.

